724319f-a.text: 4 Weehawken Street, west side, adjoining the N.W. corner of 10th Street. This is a very old frame house. March 8, 1929. P. L. Sperr.

724724f-a.text:
West Street, at, adjoining and south of the S.E. corner of West 10th Street. Building with sign atop (No. 393) is a 2-story frame house.

724726f-a.text: West Street, north from and including Pier 45, North River, and West 10th (formerly Amos) Street. This is a view taken the year before the building of the West Side Elevated Highway. March 6, 1929. P. L. Sperr.

724725f-a.text: 393, 394-395 West Street, east side, adjoining the south corner of West 10th (forme 1y Amos) Street, opposite Pier 45, North River. No. 393 is a very old wooden house; the rea faces on Weehawken Street. April 8, 1933. P. L. Sperr.

711056f-a.text: West 10th Street, west from Washington to West Streets, showing Pier No. 45 North River at the foot of same. Note the elevated railroad bed on Washington Street and the West Side Vehicular Express Highway on West  1 Street. Buildingi on the left (south side) are on a portion of the former state prison site and will be demolished in the near future to permit the erection of a 2-story garage. May 29, 1936. W.P.A. Photo. Federal Art Froject.

724324f-b.text:
1. Weehawken Street, adjoining and south of the S.W. corner of West 10th Street, showing buildings bearing Nos. 393 to 388 West Street. These structures have no Weehawken Street numbers. They are built on the former site of the Weehawken Market which was erected subsequent to the demolition of the old New York State Prison. This street being cut through at that time. The Prison occupied this, and the surrounding area between 1797 and 1829; this being its south western section. See the New York Times, Sunday, August 22, 1937 for further information. March 8, 1929. P. L. Sperr.

2. The same. May 12, 1927. P. L. Sperr.

3. A detail showing the external stairway to the upper floor of building bearing No. 393 West Street. About 1936. Gift of Dr. Michael Wishengrad, A.R.P.S.

724727f-b.text:
1. West Street, east side, from West 10th (formerly Amos) Street, opposite Pier 45, North River, to and including Charles Street, opposite Pier 46. The 1Cth Street corner is not quite all included in the picture, at the right. May 12, 1927. P. L. Sperr.

2. The same, two years later. The Holland Hotel, on the north corner of West 10th, has been brightened up. In the background, notice the old Beadleston s Woern Brewery, 10th to Charles Streets. March 8, 1929. P. L. Sperr.
